-- Refutation and Resolution
--
-- Classical: Drive toward contradiction to refute
-- CredTT: Drive credence toward 0 (degeneracy detection)
--
-- Example: Refute "sqrt(2) is rational"
-- Classical: Derive contradiction, done
-- CredTT: Show credence forced to 0

-- Classical refutation: derive False
-- CredTT refutation: drive credence to 0

-- The difference is GRADUAL vs BINARY:
-- Classical: either refuted (False) or not
-- CredTT: credence can be 0, 0.1, 0.5, 0.9, 1

-- Hypothesis to refute at credence c
postulate hypothesis : sqrt2_rational [ c ]

-- Derive consequences at same credence
derive consequence : p_and_q_coprime [ c ] from hypothesis by definition

-- Derive contradiction
derive p_even : p_is_even [ c ] from hypothesis by algebra
derive q_even : q_is_even [ c ] from p_even by algebra

-- Contradictory claims
postulate gcd_1 : gcd_is_1 [ c ]
derive gcd_2 : gcd_geq_2 [ c ] from q_even by both_even

-- Contradiction forces c = 0
contradict gcd_1 gcd_2

-- Now c = 0: hypothesis is REFUTED
-- Not "false" but "credence 0" (degenerate)

-- RESOLUTION:
-- Classical resolution: derive empty clause
-- CredTT resolution: drive credence to 0

-- The process is the same, but CredTT tracks credence throughout
-- You can see HOW FAST credence goes to 0

-- Fast refutation: one contradiction, c -> 0 immediately
-- Slow refutation: gradual accumulation of constraints

-- This matters for:
-- SAT solving: track which clauses force low credence
-- Proof complexity: measure how "hard" a refutation is
-- Debugging: find where credence drops

-- Degeneracy detection:
-- When c hits 0, we've found a degeneracy
-- This is the CredTT version of "deriving false"
